<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?t=7502&amp;p=32276#p32276"><![CDATA[
I have the problem identified at least, and ClassicShell installed and working. The clue was in the event dump file, and also I discovered that Control Panel wouldn't stay up more than a second without Explorer.exe crashing. That new event identified the same <br />Faulting module name: IDTNC64.cpl, version: 1.0.6370.0, time stamp: 0x4ea4db03<br />Faulting module path: C:\WINDOWS\system32\IDTNC64.cpl<br /><br />So I simply renamed \IDTNC64.cpl.<br /><br />Installed ClassicShell, loaded my &quot;Menu Settings.XML&quot;, running fine as is Control Panel. The &quot;Beats Audio&quot; red light on my notebook no longer illuminates, and the mute button on the RH side of the notebook is not functioning. The &quot;Beats Audio&quot; desktop app fails. <br /><br />So I would assume that Creators Update 1703 has broken my Beats Audio. There is a C:\Program Files\IDT\WDM\sttray64.exe event failing at startup. Somehow all this is affecting ClassicShell.<br /><br /><span style="font-family:Times New Roman;"><span style="font-size: 100%; line-height: 116%;">Hewlett-Packard HP ENVY 14 SPECTRE 14-3010NR, 10/20/2012</span></span><br /><span style="font-family:Times New Roman;"></span><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=19257">MerleNicholson</a> — Tue Apr 18, 2017 2:04 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
